Cranfield University said the worker returned to work three months later.
The Health and Safety Executive said three employees at the Defence Academy on the Shrivenham Campus were deactivating military cluster bomblets.
An investigation found "no suitable risk assessment had been carried out for this type of activity and therefore the system of working was unsafe".
Evan Bale of the HSE said: "The worker's injuries were life threatening and could have been avoided had a thorough assessment of the risks been carried out.
"As the university admitted, the task should not have been carried out in this manner.
"Cranfield University is properly recognised internationally for its explosives research and teaching, but in this particular case the standards for managing safety fell far short of what should have been in place."
Cranfield University said: "We deeply regret this incident and have co-operated fully with the health and safety investigation, as was accepted by the court.
"This was an isolated incident."
